\begin_layout Subsection
Vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This should be familiar from working with 2D and 3D vectors; I'm writing
 everything out to establish notation and to generalize to complex vectors.
 The space
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional real space, the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional generalization of the familiar 3D position space of classical
 physics and everyday experience.
 A point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 is described with an ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-tuple that we organize as a column vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{m}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:vec-exa}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional space of complex numbers.

\series bold
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
Transposing
\series default
\emph default
 a vector – denoted with a superscipt 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 – turns a column into a row or vice-versa; the vector in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vec-exa"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{1} & x_{2} & \cdots & x_{m}\end{array}\right]^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

To save space I'll often write vectors in this way, as transposed rows.
 When working with complex vectors, we'll find need for the complex conjugate
 of the transpose, the 
\series bold
\emph on
conjugate transpose
\series default
\emph default
.
 This will be important enough to get its own symbol, a superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}^{*}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\overline{x}_{1} & \overline{x}_{2} & \cdots & \overline{x}_{m}\end{array}\right]^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $z=a+ib$
\end_inset

, its conjugate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=a-ib$
\end_inset

.
 A superscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dagger
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\dagger$
\end_inset

 is sometimes used to denote the conjugate transpose.
 We'll use the asterisk (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

star
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) instead of the dagger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
\emph on
standard unit vectors
\series default
\emph default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{2}
\ehat_{1} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\end{array}\right]^{T}\\
\ehat_{2} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0\end{array}\right]^{T}\\
 & \vdots\\
\ehat_{m} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & \cdots & 1\end{array}\right]^{T}.
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vector arithmetic 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors add componentwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $e.g.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]^{T}+\left[y_{1},y_{2}\right]^{T}=\left[x_{1}+y_{1},x_{2}+y_{2}\right]^{T},
\]

\end_inset

and scalars multiply into all components of a vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $e.g.$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]^{T}=\left[\alpha x_{1},\alpha x_{2}\right]^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

Vectors of different sizes can't be added, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]^{T}+\left[y_{1},y_{2},y_{3}\right]^{T}
\]

\end_inset

is nonsense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dot product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dot product between two vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}x_{j}y_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

We won't use dot product notation much; we'll usually write the same expression
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}^{T}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 With complex vectors, the 
\emph on
conjugate
\emph default
 transpose should be normally be used:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}^{*}\mathbf{y}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}\overline{x}_{j}y_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Magnitude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
\emph on
magnitude
\series default
\emph default
 of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

, and is computed using the Pythagorean formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert =\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+\cdots+x_{m}^{2}}=\sqrt{\mathbf{x}^{T}\mathbf{x}}.
\]

\end_inset

If the vector is complex, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

, then this is slightly modified, using the conjugate transpose in place
 of the transpose,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\left|x_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|x_{2}\right|^{2}+\cdots+\left|x_{m}\right|^{2}}=\sqrt{\mathbf{x}^{*}\mathbf{x}}.
\]

\end_inset

Recall that the magnitude of a complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a+ib$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right|=\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}=\sqrt{z\overline{z}}.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}=a_{j}+ib_{j}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert =\sqrt{a_{1}^{2}+b_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\cdots+a_{m}^{2}+b_{m}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\cdots,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 each in 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

, we can form an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
\emph on
matrix
\series default
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by putting the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

 into the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
\mathbf{a}_{1} & \mathbf{a}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{a}_{n}\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

If we denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}$
\end_inset

, then the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is written
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & \cdots\\
A_{21} & A_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Like vectors, matrices add componentwise and a scalar multiplying into a
 matrix multiplies all components:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & \cdots\\
A_{21} & A_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
B_{11} & B_{12} & \cdots\\
B_{21} & B_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11}+B_{11} & A_{12}+B_{12} & \cdots\\
A_{21}+B_{21} & A_{22}+B_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & \cdots\\
A_{21} & A_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\alpha A_{11} & \alpha A_{12} & \cdots\\
\alpha A_{21} & \alpha A_{22}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

The set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 real matrices is called 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

.
 The analogue for complex matrices is 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear combinations and matrix-vector multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Core definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that notation has been described, we can establish some definitions
 that will be fundamental to our study of linear algebra and differential
 equations.
 I'll write out all the definitions with some commentary, and only afterwards
 give some examples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the definitions that follow, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} _{j=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}\in\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 All the definitions will be stated in terms of complex spaces; to restrict
 the definitions to real spaces, replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear combination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a term we'll use often, so we might as well define it formally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\series bold
\emph on
linear combination
\series default
\emph default
 (LC) of the members of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a scalar-weighted sum such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}_{1}x_{1}+\mathbf{a}_{2}x_{2}+\cdots+\mathbf{a}_{n}x_{n},
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} _{j=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are scalars.
 The 
\series bold
\emph on
span
\series default
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Span\left(S\right)$
\end_inset

, is the set of all linear combinations that can be formed from the members
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vector spaces and subspaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:vec-space"

\end_inset

A set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of vectors is called a 
\series bold
\emph on
vector space
\series default
\emph default
 if it obeys the axioms listed in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Formal-definition-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We needn't go into all the axioms for this course; as long as one defines
 addition and scalar multiplication 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reasonably,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 then it is sufficient to consider the 
\series bold
\emph on
closure conditions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\in U$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\in U$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\mathbf{x}\in U$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in U$
\end_inset

 and for all scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the 
\series bold
\shape italic
zero condition
\series default
,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 contains the zero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sub
\emph on
set
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 that is itself a vector space is called a 
\series bold
\emph on
subspace
\series default
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The closure conditions mean that if you form a LC of members of a subspace
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, the result must be in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Like they say about Las Vegas, whatever happens in a vector space stays
 in that vector space.
 You'd have to use some imagination to come up with a set that obeys the
 closure and zero conditions but isn't a vector space, and such cases aren't
 anything we'd encounter in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will assert without proof that the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

 are vector spaces.
 A useful result, also stated without proof, is the 
\series bold
\emph on
subspace theorem
\series default
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Subspace theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a vector space, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 satisfies the closure conditions from Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:vec-space"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a vector space (and therefore a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For subspaces, the zero condition is implied by the closure conditions (to
 prove this, consider the operations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

).
 Often the easiest way to show something is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a subspace is to check the zero condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix-vector multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several equivalent
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The equivalent definitions of matrix-vector multiplication will all produce
 the same results.
 We choose the one that is most useful for 
\emph on
understanding
\emph default
 how to use matrices for solving differential equations.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ways to define matrix vector multiplication (see Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:mvmult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For our purposes, it will be most useful to think of multiplication of
 a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 as forming a linear combination of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, weighted by the entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Form the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\CC^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 by packing the members of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 into its columns.
 Given a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
\emph on
matrix-vector
\series default
\emph default
 
\series bold
\emph on
product
\series default
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

is the linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

's weighted by the entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

