\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Null space and range space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\series bold
\emph on
null space
\series default
\emph default
 (sometimes called the 
\series bold
\emph on
kernel
\series default
\emph default
) of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\CC^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, is the set of vectors 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x=0}.$
\end_inset

 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all solutions to the homogeneous equation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 always contains the zero vector.
 If a null space contains 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 the zero vector, that null space is called 
\series bold
\emph on
trivial
\series default
\emph default
; otherwise, it is called 
\series bold
\emph on
nontrivial
\series default
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this definition isn't casual: By working with the subspace theorem and
 the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, it is not hard to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear independence/dependence and the null space are intimately related:
 from the definitions of LI and the null space, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is trivial iff the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are LI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preview: the 
\emph on
eigenvalue problem
\emph default
 will be to identify when a certain matrix has a nontrivial null space,
 and then finding the members of that null space.
 The eigenvalue problem will be essential in solving systems of ODEs and
 also PDEs, so perk up your ears whenever you hear 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

null space.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\series bold
\emph on
range space
\series default
\emph default
 or 
\series bold
\emph on
column space
\series default
\emph default
 of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Range\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Col\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, is the set of all linear combinations of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Range\left(A\right)=\left\{ \mathbf{y}:\exists\mathbf{x}\;\text{such that }\mathbf{y}=A\mathbf{x}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Notice that we can also view this as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Range\left(A\right)=\Span\left(\text{columns of }A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The range space of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set of vectors that can be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reached
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by matrix-vector multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The theorem follows immediately from the definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:solnInRange"

\end_inset

The problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 has a solution iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\in\Range\left(A\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with the null space, the range space is a vector space.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Range\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Range\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

; when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 isn't square, 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\CC^{n}$
\end_inset

 aren't the same spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 is in the range of every matrix, with preimage 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
\emph on
basis
\series default
\emph default
 for a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is LI and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Span\left(B\right)=V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

