\begin_layout Section
Systems of equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Central to our study of differential equations will be this: represent a
 function (say, a solution to a DE) as a linear combination of convenient
 functions (say, exponentials, polynomials, or trig functions).
 We'll start with a simpler problem: representing a specified vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\in\RR^{m}$
\end_inset

 as a LC of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Not only will this be illustrative of more general problems, it will be
 useful in its own right.
 This problem takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{m}\mathbf{a}_{j}x_{j}=\mathbf{b}
\]

\end_inset

which we can write compactly as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
