\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
-\frac{3}{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right];\;\;\;\;\mathbf{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
9\\
-6
\end{array}\right];\;\;\;\;\mathbf{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
-360\\
240
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and so on.
 Of course 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 is a solution as well.
 All of these solutions can be represented as follows: choose 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 solution, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=-2$
\end_inset

, introduce a scalar parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and write the solution to the problem as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=s\left[\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

This can represent any solution simply by changing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
