\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With some examples in hand, let's analyze the nonhomogeneous problem in
 general.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By looking at the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Null\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 and the homogeneous problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, notice that the set of solutions to the homogeneous problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If the only solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 (and remember, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 will 
\emph on
always 
\emph default
solve the homogeneous problem) then the null space is trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's now consider the more complicated case of nontrivial solutions.
 This will occur iff row reduction produces one or more rows of zeros.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 nonzero rows there will be 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

