\begin_layout Section
Matrix-matrix multiplication and the inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You've probably learned how to do matrix-matrix multiplication, but might
 not have been told 
\emph on
why
\emph default
 it's defined in such a strange way.
 Here's the fundamental idea: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrix-matrix multiplication is defined so that the operations 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 give the same result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all, notice that the output of 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 must have the same dimension as the input to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must have 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 columns.
 The matrix-matrix product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 is defined only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times n$
\end_inset

; the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

middle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dimension must be the same.
 If the matrices have the right combination of shapes for 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 to make sense, we call them 
\series bold
\emph on
compatible
\series default
\emph default
.
 Note that two square matrices of the same size are always compatible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The matrix-matrix multiplication formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are compatible.
 We're going to 
\emph on
derive
\emph default
 the formula for the matrix-matrix product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 by working out 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 and insisting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 must give the same result.
 First, use the column-wise form of matrix-vector multiplication to write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\mathbf{x}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\mathbf{b}_{j}x_{j}
\]

\end_inset

and then multiply through (from the left) by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)=A\sum_{j=1}^{n}\mathbf{b}_{j}x_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{j=1}^{n}A\mathbf{b}_{j}x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

That's 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to get the same answer.
 We don't (yet) know what the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 actually look like, but we do know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the LC of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 weighted by the entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left[j-\text{th column of }AB\right]x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

We can now determine the unknown expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[j-\text{th column of }AB\right]$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\sum_{j=1}^{n}A\mathbf{b}_{j}x_{j}}_{A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)}=\underbrace{\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left[j-\text{th column of }AB\right]x_{j}}_{\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}}
\]

\end_inset

Comparing the vectors in each sum, we see that the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{b}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the matrix-matrix product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 is the matrix written out columnwise as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
AB=\left[\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
A\mathbf{b}_{1} & A\mathbf{b}_{2} & \cdots & A\mathbf{b}_{n}\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

This is a simple formula to follow for hand calculation, and it will also
 be important theoretically in eigenvalue analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedImportant

\series bold
Pro tip
\series default
: when computing 
\begin_inset Formula $AB\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, it's usually more efficient to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 first, then multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into the result, than it is to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 then multiply into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 This is true for hand calculations and for computer calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An alternate derivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's an alternate derivation of matrix-matrix multiplication using the
 summation form of the matrix-vector product.
 Start by computing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

-th entry in 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, which we write out in summation form as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)_{\ell}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}B_{\ell j}x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

Then multiply from the left by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, writing the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry in the result as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)\right]_{i}=\sum_{\ell=1}^{k}A_{i\ell}\left(\sum_{j=1}^{n}B_{\ell j}x_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{k}A_{i\ell}B_{\ell j}\right)x_{j}\;\;\;\;\left(\text{exchange order of summation}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now recognize that this is just matrix-vector multiplication of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 by the matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 element is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\ell=1}^{k}A_{i\ell}B_{\ell j}.
\]

\end_inset

You should convince yourself that the 
\begin_inset Formula $j-$
\end_inset

th column of this matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{b}_{j}$
\end_inset

, as found above.
 
\end_layout

