\begin_layout Subsection
The matrix inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we know about matrix-matrix products, we ask whether we can find
 a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with which we can solve the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}
\]

\end_inset

by multiplication, similarly to how we use the reciprocal of a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $ax=b$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the identity matrix, and suppose that for a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\series bold
\emph on
inverse matrix
\series default
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{-1}A=I.
\]

\end_inset

Then, solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 follows immediately: multiply through by 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 from the left,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{-1}A\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b}.
\]

\end_inset

Hooray, the equation has been solved! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedBad
Application of a matrix inverse is 
\series bold
\emph on
not
\series default
\emph default
 division by a matrix, so 
\series bold
\emph on
never
\series default
\emph default
 write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=\frac{\mathbf{b}}{A}.
\]

\end_inset

Division by matrices and vectors is never allowed!
\end_layout

