\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a few pending questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 have an inverse? (and is it unique, etc)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does have an inverse, how do we find it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has an inverse and we know how to find it, is using the inverse to compute
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 an efficient way to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our answer to the first question will be 
\emph on
constructive
\emph default
, meaning that we will show the existence of an inverse by giving an algorithm
 to 
\emph on
construct 
\emph default
one; thus, we will answer the second question (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how do we find it?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) along the way to answering the question of existence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before embarking on construction of an inverse, let's think about when we'd
 expect 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 to have one.
 An inverse applied by matrix-vector multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 should produce exactly one solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, and it should break down when the problem has no solution.
 By the nature of matrix-vector multiplication the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 can't produce more than one result.
 Furthermore, matrix-vector multiplication can't ever break down.
 To avoid nonsense results we expect 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to fail to exists whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 We will see that this is the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constructing the inverse 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 by 
\emph on
superposition.
 
\emph default
The basic idea is this: 
\emph on
build up a solution to an equation by summing simpler solutions to simpler
 problems.
 
\emph default
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simpler
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problems will be 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}_{j}=\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 These aren't really any simpler, but bear with me.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
 Let's write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 as a LC of standard Cartesian unit vectors,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{b}=b_{1}\ehat_{1}+b_{2}\ehat_{2}+\cdots+b_{n}\ehat_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Suppose we've solved each of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problems 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}_{j}=\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

 for the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to the original problem is, by superposition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=b_{1}\mathbf{x}_{1}+b_{2}\mathbf{x}_{2}+\cdots+b_{n}\mathbf{x}_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Glue the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

 into the columns of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=X\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular there is a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=X\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of the inverse, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=X$
\end_inset

.
 Every nonsingular matrix has an inverse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, if you're paying attention, you'll see that we've actually shown
 to to construct the inverse.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}_{j}$
\end_inset

, formed by solving 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{z}_{j}=\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular, each of those 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problems has a unique solution; therefore, the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 formed from those solutions is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Will this procedure work if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

