\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has an inverse iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
 That inverse is unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
We've already shown that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular, then it has a unique inverse.
 For the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

only if
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 direction: if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular, then row reduction on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (possibly involving row exchanges) will produce at least one row of nonzeros.
 For simplicity, focus on the case where there are no row exchanges, and
 suppose that (at least) the final row 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is entirely zero.
 We'll need to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}_{m}=\ehat_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 When we form the augmented matrix for that problem, it will look like this:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc|c}
u_{11} & u_{12} & \cdots & u_{1m} & 0\\
0 & u_{22} &  &  & 0\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

This is because the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-th (bottom) row is formed as a linear combination of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with nonzero multiples of the rows above it.
 But since all entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat_{m}$
\end_inset

 save the last are zero, that process leaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat_{m}$
\end_inset

 unchanged, and as a result the equation encoded in the final row has no
 solution.
 Therefore, the construction of the inverse must fail for at least one of
 the unit vectors, and the inverse cannot exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a linear algebra class, you might have learned to compute the inverse
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by setting up the augmented system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
A & I\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and doing Gauss-Jordan elimination; after that process the inverse will
 be in the second block column of the augmented system.
 Now you can see why that works: the procedure solves the equations 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{z}_{j}=\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

 simultaneously in the same table, with the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}_{j}$
\end_inset

 being written into the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of the second block column.
 In practice, you'd not do Gauss-Jordan elimination; you'd do Gaussian eliminati
on followed by backsubstitution to find each column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If you ever need to compute an inverse – and you probably don't – do it
 with Gaussian elimination and backsubstitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Don't compute an inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that I've shown you how to compute an inverse, I'm going to tell you
 never to do it.
 Well, almost never.
 It's a matter of efficiency.
 Notice that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problems 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{z}_{j}=\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

 that arose in the computation of the inverse were, in fact, no smaller
 or easier than the original problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 You might conclude from that observation that computing the inverse isn't
 such a useful idea after all, and you'd be right.
 As a general rule, 
\emph on
don't compute a matrix inverse
\emph default
.
 Just solve the system 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You might think that if you're solving 
\emph on
many
\emph default
 systems 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x=}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 but different RHS vectors
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is very common in practice.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdots,$
\end_inset

 then the up-front cost invested in computing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 might save time in the long run when solving the sequence of systems.
 My undergraduate linear algebra textbook, and my teacher, claimed this;
 they were wrong.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Mtx-Inverses-Bad"

\end_inset

 for an explanation of why that is, and for the right way to solve multiple
 systems of equations efficiently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So if we shouldn't compute it, what good is the inverse?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is most useful as 
\emph on
notation
\emph default
.
 When I write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 I mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solve the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 using any efficient method you like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Keeping in mind the Pro Tip on how to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 (
\series bold
\emph on
don't
\series default
\emph default
 do the matrix-matrix multiplications to form 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC$
\end_inset

), this lets you make sense out of what to do with expressions like 
\begin_inset Formula $ABA^{-1}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 You can evaluate that with (a) no inverse computations and (b) no matrix-matrix
 multiplications, as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}=A^{-1}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 by solving 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{p}=\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 using, 
\emph on
e.g., 
\emph default
Gaussian elimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=B\left(A^{-1}\mathbf{y}\right)$
\end_inset

 by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 computed in the first step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=A\left(B\left(A^{-1}\mathbf{y}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 computed in the second step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedure takes one run of Gaussian elimination plus two matrix-vector
 multiplies, compared to the 
\emph on
much
\emph default
 more expensive proposition of one inverse calculation and two matrix-matrix
 multiplies.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sometimes the inverse can be found easily and efficiently.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Nonsingular diagonal matrices are trivially inverted: just take the reciprocals
 of the diagonal entries.
 If one of the diagonal entries is zero then the matrix is singular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is a simple formula for the inverse of a two-by-two matrix.
 The formula is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right)^{-1}=\frac{1}{ad-bc}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
d & -b\\
-c & a
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

For a general two-by two system, using this formula is about as efficient
 as any other method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inverses of 
\emph on
orthogonal 
\emph default
matrices and 
\emph on
unitary 
\emph default
matrices (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Orthogonal-and-unitary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be found with no calculations at all.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Some properties of the inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A^{-1}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an invertible matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a scalar, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha A\right)^{-1}=\frac{1}{\alpha}A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inverse of a product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 is the product of the inverses, in reversed order: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)^{-1}=B^{-1}A^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here's why: to solve the system 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
AB\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b},
\]

\end_inset

you would first solve 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(B\mathbf{x}\right)=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 for the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\mathbf{x}=A^{-1}\mathbf{b},
\]

\end_inset

and then solve that system for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}=B^{-1}A^{-1}\mathbf{b}.
\]

\end_inset

Since this is the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(AB\right)\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(AB\right)^{-1}=B^{-1}A^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those are some things you can do with inverses.
 Here's something that 
\emph on
doesn't
\emph default
 work, however desperate one might be to solve a problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedBad

\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedBad
The inverse of a sum is 
\series bold
\emph on
not
\series default
\emph default
 , in general, the sum of the inverses:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A+B\right)^{-1}\ne A^{-1}+B^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove the formula false, a single counterexample is sufficient: try 
\begin_inset Formula $B=-A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A+B\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, but it is an infinite series (similar to the familiar geometric series
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a+b\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are real).
 I will not state it here, because the convergence conditions involve concepts
