LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-det-perm"

\end_inset

The determinant of a permutation matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A permutation matrix applied to the identity exchanges two or more of the
 legs in the parallelepiped.
 One exchange reverses the orientation and thus has determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Two exchanges reverses the orientation twice, and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:singular-det"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start with a simple case: we'll first show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is triangular, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(T\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 Start in 2D, and WLOG suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T_{11} & T_{12}\\
0 & T_{22}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

The parallelogram formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 has one leg of length 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{11}$
\end_inset

 along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis, and another along the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T_{12} & T_{22}\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The parallelogram collapses to a line iff the second leg has no component
 along the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis, that is, iff 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{22}=0$
\end_inset

.
 But from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Triangular-matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is singular iff if it contains zero on the diagonal.
 Therefore, a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 triangular matrix has zero determinant iff it is singular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
T_{11} & T_{12} & T_{13}\\
0 & T_{22} & T_{23}\\
0 & 0 & T_{33}\\
 &  &  & \ddots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and think about the volume formed by the three columns.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{11}$
\end_inset

 is zero, then we have a zero leg and the volume collapses to zero.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{22}$
\end_inset

 is zero, then the first two legs are parallel and the volume collapses
 to zero.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{33}=0$
\end_inset

, then leg 3 is coplanar with legs 1 and 2, and the volume collapses to
 zero.
 And so on.
 If any diagonal entry is zero, then the volume is zero.
 If no diagonal entries are zero, then each successive column extends into
 a dimension not yet 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

explored
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by the others, so the volume is nonzero.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular, make the same argument starting with the last column.
 Therefore: if 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is triangular, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(T\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why spend so much time on triangular matrices? Because the operations of
 row reduction (other than row exchanges) can be represented as multiplication
 by lower triangular matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ignoring row exchanges, row reduction of an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to an upper triangular matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{1}L_{2}\cdots L_{m-1}A=U,
\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular with ones on the diagonal.
 Given that restriction on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(L_{i}\right)\ne0$
\end_inset

.
 Using the determinant product formula, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(L_{1}\right)\det\left(L_{2}\right)\cdots\det\left(L_{m-1}\right)\det\left(A\right)=\det\left(U\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since none of the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

's have zero determinants, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(U\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 will have a zero on the diagonal, and therefore a zero determinant, iff
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We're almost there.
 What about row exchanges? Row exchanges are represented by permutation
 matrices.
 Row reduction becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{1}L_{1}P_{2}L_{2}\cdots P_{m-1}L_{m-1}A=U.
\]

\end_inset

But from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-det-perm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(P_{i}\right)\ne0$
\end_inset

, so we reach the same conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedImportant
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this course, this will be the most important property of the determinant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The determinant of an inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}A=I$
\end_inset

.
 From the product formula, find
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(A^{-1}\right)\det\left(A\right)=\det\left(I\right),
\]

\end_inset

and then conclude 
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedImportant
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(A^{-1}\right)=\frac{1}{\det\left(A\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A^{-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is undefined iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

, which is to be expected since 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular: a singular matrix has no inverse!
\end_layout

