\begin_layout Subsection
Why you should 
\emph on
never
\emph default
 use a floating point determinant calculation to check for singularity of
 a matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since I'm a computational mathematician, I'm morally obligated to warn you
 about ways to screw up when using a computer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probably the most important property of the determinant is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular.
 This is useful and we'll use this often when working with eigenvalues.
 But beware: 
\series bold
\emph on
never
\series default
\emph default
 use this as a test for singularity when working in floating point arithmetic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you have two matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 , and find after floating point calculation that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(A\right)\approx10^{-18}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(B\right)\approx10.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-18}$
\end_inset

 is smaller than machine precision and 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 is bigger, it's tempting to conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is singular and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is not.
 But you would be wrong.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has to do with scaling.
 Remember: 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a hypervolume.
 Scaling an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The hypervolume of a six-dimensional hypercube, one meter on a side, is
 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,\text{m}^{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Now find the volume of that same box, but working in kilometers.
 Each side is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-3}$
\end_inset

 km in length, for a hypervolume of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-18}\,\text{km}^{6}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of the determinant depends on the units you choose, and the problem
 gets worse the higher the dimension of the problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedImportant
In floating point calculations, a very small determinant does 
\series bold
\emph on
not
\series default
\emph default
 imply a singular matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, we can't trust very small determinants to indicate singular matrices.
 But can we at least trust a moderate size determinant to indicate a nonsingular
 matrix? Alas, no.
 The problem is accumulation of roundoff error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cramer's Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't use it.
 Use Gaussian elimination instead.
 If your problem too large for Gaussian elimination (in which case it will
 be 
\emph on
much
\emph default
 too large to use Cramer's Rule) use an iterative method such as conjugate
 gradients, GMRES, or multilevel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why avoid Cramer's Rule? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you compute all the determinants the smart, efficient, and robust way,
 doing LU factorizations instead of expansions in minors, it will take you
 
\begin_inset Formula $m+1$
\end_inset

 LU factorizations.
 Gaussian elimination requires one LU factorization.
 Cramer's Rule takes 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times the work of Gaussian elimination, and that's if you do it the smart
 way.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:How-to-wait"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for what you can expect if you do it the dumb way.
 
\end_layout

