\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:mvmult"

\end_inset

Three ways of looking at matrix-vector multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 a vector of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 .
 Then the matrix vector product 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 can be defined in the three equivalent ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the vector formed by the LC of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{cols}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 weighted by the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{a}_{1}x_{1}+\mathbf{a}_{2}x_{2}+\cdots+\mathbf{a}_{n}x_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the vector whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A\mathbf{x}\right)_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}A_{ij}x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the vector whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry is the dot product between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You should convince yourself that the three ways of doing matrix-vector
 multiplication are equivalent.
 The order matters: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as above; 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}A$
\end_inset

 is nonsense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 by hand, most of us use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dot product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 method (#3 in the list); it's more convenient.
 However, for understanding the applications of matrices, the summation
 (#2) or the LC method (#1) will be more useful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You should also convince yourself of the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrix-vector multiplication distributes over linear combinations: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(\alpha\mathbf{x}+\beta\mathbf{y}\right)=\alpha A\mathbf{x}+\beta A\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrix-vector multiplication and matrix-matrix addition are defined consistently
, meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A+B\right)\mathbf{x}=A\mathbf{x}+B\mathbf{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

