\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Gaussian-elimination"

\end_inset

Refresher: Gaussian elimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You've very likely seen row reduction
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
row reduction
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and Gaussian elimination
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian elimination
\end_layout

\end_inset

 before.
 Recall that we solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 by constructing an augmented matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
A & b\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, then doing row operations to put the augmented matrix in row echelon form.
 The solution can then by computed by backsubstitution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to my presentation here, you might look at the very good MIT
 OpenCourseWare video at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xCIXkm3-ocQ
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in which an example is worked out in detail.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simplest case: no row exchanges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's solve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 2\\
2 & 1 & 3\\
1 & 1 & 5
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
c_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
2
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

in this way.
 Form the augmented matrix.
 The element to be eliminated is circled; the row operation that eliminates
 it is indicated above the arrow.
 Start by eliminating the 2,1 element: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
\circled{2} & 1 & 3 & 0\\
1 & 1 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{2}\gets R_{2}-2R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\\
1 & 1 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Then the 3,1 element
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\\
\circled{1} & 1 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{3}\gets R_{3}-R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\\
0 & 1 & 3 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the 3,2 element
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\\
0 & \circled{1} & 3 & 1
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{3}\gets R_{3}-R_{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\\
0 & 0 & 4 & 3
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

The system is now in row echelon form so we're ready to do backsubsitution.
 Work up from the bottom: the third row encodes an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & 4 & 3\end{array}\right] & \mbox{\;\;\;means} & 4c_{3}=3 & \mbox{\;\;so} & c_{3}=\frac{3}{4}\end{aligned}
.
\]

\end_inset

Then use the second row to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 1 & -1 & -2\end{array}\right] & \mbox{\;\;\;means} & c_{2}-c_{3}=-2 & \mbox{\;\;so} & c_{2}=-2+\frac{3}{4}=-\frac{5}{4}\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and the first row to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 1\end{array}\right] & \mbox{\;\;\;means} & c_{1}+0c_{2}+2c_{3}=1 & \mbox{\;\;so} & c_{1}=1-\frac{3}{2}=-\frac{1}{2}.\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Elimination with row exchanges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes you'll encounter a zero on the diagonal.
 That's a problem, because you can't use it to eliminate entries below it
 and ultimately because you'll need to divide by the diagonal entries..
 When you hit a zero on the diagonal, swap rows until you find a nonzero.
 Here we solve the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 1 & 2\\
2 & 2 & 3\\
1 & 2 & 5
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
c_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
2
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

The first step introduces a zero on the diagonal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
\circled{2} & 2 & 3 & 0\\
1 & 2 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{2}\gets R_{2}-2R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & {\color{red}0} & -1 & -2\\
1 & 2 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which causes no problems with the next step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & -2\\
\circled{1} & 2 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{3}\gets R_{3}-R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & {\color{red}0} & -1 & -2\\
0 & 1 & 3 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

but at this point, we can't use rows 2 and 3 to eliminate the 3,2 entry
 because the 2,2 entry is zero.
 (Why can't we just use row 1 to eliminate 3,2? Think about it: what would
 go wrong if we did that?) So swap rows 2 and 3, moving the zero away from
 the diagonal.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & -2\\
0 & 1 & 3 & 1
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{2}\leftrightarrows R_{3}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 3 & 1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & -2
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Now the matrix is in row echelon form (in a large system we might have additiona
l rows to reduce, but with only 3 rows we're done).
 Do backsubstitution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{3}=2
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=1-3c_{3}=-5
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=1-c_{2}-2c_{3}=2.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
When Gaussian elimination fails
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, in some cases we may be unable to clear all zeros from the
 diagonal.
 Here's such a case: try to solve
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 1 & 2\\
1 & 2 & 3\\
0 & 1 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
c_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
2
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Eliminate the 2,1 entry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
\circled{1} & 2 & 3 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 1 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{2}\gets R_{2}-R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & 2
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The 3,1 entry happened to be zero so we can skip that step.
 Move on to eliminate the 3,2 entry: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & \circled{1} & 1 & 2
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{3}\gets R_{3}-R_{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 3
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Oops.
 We could eliminate 3,2 but in doing so we also killed 3,3.
 There are no more rows to swap, so we're stuck with a zero diagonal.
 Now the row
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & 0 & 3\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

is shorthand for the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0c_{1}+0c_{2}+0c_{3}=3
\]

\end_inset

which has no solution for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system where after row reduction we have one or more zeros on the diagonal
 is called 
\emph on
singular.
 
\emph default
A case such as this one, where no solution was found, is called 
\emph on
singular and inconsistent
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consistent versus inconsistent singular systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous example we had no solution.
 That's not always the case.
 Consider the slightly different problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 1 & 2\\
1 & 2 & 3\\
0 & 1 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
c_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
-1
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Notice that the matrix is the same, but the right hand side differs in the
 3rd entry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceed with Gaussian elimination: eliminate the 2,1 entry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
\circled{1} & 2 & 3 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 1 & 1
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{2}\gets R_{2}-R_{1}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

skip the 3,3 entry (which is already zero) and eliminate the 3,2 entry:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & \circled{1} & 1 & -1
\end{array}\right]\ua{R_{3}\gets R_{3}-R_{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 2 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1 & -1\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Once again, we killed the diagonal 3,3, but the final row is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & 0 & 0\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

is shorthand for the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0c_{1}+0c_{2}+0c_{3}=0.
\]

\end_inset

This equation can be solved by 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Ordinarily, we'd use the final row to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

, but in this case, we can't determine 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

 since any 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

 will do.
 So let's pick 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

 to be an arbitrary parameter, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then proceed back to the second row,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0c_{1}+c_{2}+c_{3}=-1
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{2}=-1-\alpha.
\]

\end_inset

Use the first row to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}+c_{2}+2c_{3}=1
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
