\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you need to solve two systems having the same matrix but different
 right-hand sides: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}_{1}=\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{x}_{2}=\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 You could go through Gaussian elimination twice, but if you think about
 it when you do row reduction on the two different augmented matrices you're
 doing exactly the same operations on all but the final column of the augmented
 matrices.
 It would probably occur to you to record both the sequence of operations
 and the final upper triangular form.
 Then, when solving a new system you could do the recorded operations to
 the right-hand side vector and then do backsubstitution against the recorded
 upper triangular form to find the solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sure enough, somebody
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
