\end_layout

\end_inset

has already thought to do just that.
 Remarkably, all the row operations can be recorded in a convenient form
 as a product of a permutation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 times a lower triangular matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}$
\end_inset

 having ones on the diagonal.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L^{-1}PA=U
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PA=LU.
\]

\end_inset

A permutation matrix is an identity matrix with certain rows exchanged;
 multiplication from the left by a permutation matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $PA$
\end_inset

, produces a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with rows exchanged as specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 Permutation matrices have the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}=P^{T}$
\end_inset

, so that it is easy to solve systems involving 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (this shouldn't be surprising; to apply 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}$
\end_inset

 simply undo the row exchange done by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

).
 What is surprising is that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}$
\end_inset

 which records the row operations can be inverted very simply with no calculatio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you've factored 
\begin_inset Formula $A=P^{T}LU$
\end_inset

, you can solve a system 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 with two triangular solves: first solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Ly=Pb$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Ux=y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Triangular solves require backsubstitution, which is easy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Mtx-Inverses-Bad"

\end_inset

Why you shouldn't compute a matrix inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost (in floating point operations) of doing row reduction on an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix to upper triangular form by Gaussian elimination with row pivoting
 works out to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}m^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The LU factorization is simply a convenient encoding of that algorithm,
 with no extra cost.
 The cost formula can be derived by induction, but it's more useful to understan
d it as follows: to do row reduction, you need to eliminate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx\frac{1}{2}m^{2}$
\end_inset

 entries below the diagonal.
 To kill each subdiagonal entry you need to do one row operation.
 Each 
\emph on
full length 
\emph default
row operation takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx2m$
\end_inset

 elementary floating point arithmetic operations (flops), so a first estimate
 for the cost would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx m^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 But notice that as you proceed through the algorithm, the columns already
 zeroed out can be ignored so the row operations become cheaper as you go,
 making the 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}$
\end_inset

 estimate an overestimate.
 The exact factor can be worked out (pretty easily), and it turns out to
 be 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I'll ignore pivots (row exchanges) because they don't change the operation
 counts; there's a slight cost to pivoting because indirect addressing is
 necessary, but for moderate size dense matrices (up to a few thousand)
 the whole thing fits in cache memory so addressing is essentially free.
 To include pivots, just write 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{T}LU$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a permutation matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you've factored 
\begin_inset Formula $A=LU$
\end_inset

, you can solve a system 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 with two triangular solves: first solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Ly=b$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Ux=y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The cost of one triangular solve is 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}$
\end_inset

 flops (you do two operations with half the elements, so twice 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}/2$
\end_inset

).
 So solving 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 with one RHS costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}m^{3}+2m^{2}.$
\end_inset

 Solving 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 systems with different right-hand sides costs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\frac{2}{3}m^{3}}_{LU\mbox{ factorization}}+\underbrace{2rm^{2}}_{2r\mbox{ triangular solves}}.
\]

\end_inset

Now compare to the cost of solving these systems by computing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 once, then multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 by each of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 right-hand sides.
 To find 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

, solve the system 
\begin_inset Formula $AX=I$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The best way to do this is to factor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $LU$
\end_inset

, then use it to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $AX_{j}=e_{j}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of the identity) using the method above.
 Since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 such systems to solve, the cost of forming the inverse is given by the
 formula above with 
\begin_inset Formula $r=m$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{8}{3}m^{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that you have the inverse, solving 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 requires a matrix-vector multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $x=A^{-1}b$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that each matrix-vector multiplication costs 
\begin_inset Formula $2m^{2}$
\end_inset

 operations.
 Doing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 matrix-vector multiplications requires 
\begin_inset Formula $2rm^{2}$
\end_inset

 operations, exactly the same as the cost of doing the triangular solves
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $LU$
\end_inset

 method; that is, once you've formed 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 the marginal cost of solving one more system is exactly the same as if
 you'd simply stored 
\begin_inset Formula $LU$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, since you already had to find 
\begin_inset Formula $LU$
\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{=1}$
\end_inset

, finding and using the inverse is never cost effective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost of factoring 
\begin_inset Formula $A=LU$
\end_inset

, then doing 2 triangular solves for each of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 right-hand sides: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\frac{2}{3}m^{3}}_{LU\mbox{ factorization}}+\underbrace{2rm^{2}}_{2r\mbox{ triangular solves}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost of computing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

, then doing matrix-vector multiplication for each of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 right-hand sides:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\frac{2}{3}m^{3}}_{LU\mbox{ factorization}}+\underbrace{2m^{3}r}_{2m\mbox{ triangular solves to find }A^{-1}}+\underbrace{2rm^{2}}_{r\mbox{ matrix-vector multiplications \ensuremath{A^{-1}b}}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=2m^{3}\;\;\mbox{overhead beyond solving the same problem without the inverse.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elementary textbooks often say that you only compute an inverse when you're
 going to solve multiple systems, but you can now see that even then it's
 simply not efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You might use an inverse in cases where forming the inverse is trivial:
 for example, to invert a diagonal matrix just replace the diagonal elements
 by their reciprocals.
 Another important example is an orthogonal matrix, where the inverse turns
 out to be the transpose, no need for any calculations.
 Finally, there's a simple formula for the inverse of a two-by-two matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\frac{1}{ad-bc}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
d & -b\\
-c & a
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

that's handy for quick calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any real production calculation, 
\series bold
\emph on
you should never compute a non-trivial inverse
\series default
\emph default
.
 And 
\series bold
\emph on
never, never use Cramer's Rule with Laplace expansion of the determinant
 for numerical calculation
\series default
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Computing determinants numerically
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first thing to say is this: If you think you need to compute a determinant
 numerically, you probably don't.
 There's really only one reason to compute one, and that's if you need to
 compute a volume or hypervolume.
 If you're doing a numerical integral, yep, you'll need a determinant.
 Otherwise, probably not.
 If you're thinking of computing a determinant numerically to solve a system
 or to compute eigenvalues, stop now and read about the right ways to do
 those calculations.
 The right ways don't involve determinants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Okay, suppose you really do need to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 for some numerical matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Here's how.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use your favorite LU factorization code to factor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $PLU$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a permutation matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular with ones on the diagonal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

